title: For Sale:  Know Your Rights Kentucky!
postcontent:
Know your rights concerning the carry of firearms in Kentucky!  If you don't know the law or you have been given INCORRECT advice then you need to visit this forum and speak with us and search the threads!

I've heard many people say that "you cannot carry a firearm loaded in your vehicle" or that "you cannot carry one openly on your person unless you have a KY CDWL."  This is COMPLETELY FALSE!  

You only need a CDWL in KY to CONCEAL a deadly weapon, but you can also carry concealed without a license in certain places (KRS 527.020).

Kentucky firearm laws can be found here:
http://lrc.ky.gov/KRS/237-00/CHAPTER.HTM
and
http://lrc.ky.gov/KRS/527-00/CHAPTER.HTM

There is also a statute here:
http://lrc.ky.gov/KRS/244-00/125.PDF

The Court of Justice can prohibit firearms in their facilities under authority of this statute:
http://lrc.ky.gov/KRS/447-00/154.PDF

OPENLY carried firearms are NOT prohibited in all of the places where CONCEALED firearms are prohibited because the right to OPENLY carry a firearm and other deadly weapons is protected by the KY Constitution with KY Supreme Court precedent:
http://www.kc3.com/Holland%20v%20Commonwealth.htm

Kentucky has STRONG firearm preemption and NO ONE in the state can regulate firearms, ammunition or components except the General Assembly: 
http://lrc.ky.gov/KRS/065-00/870.PDF

Places where openly carried firearms are prohibited:

K-12 schools unless exempted under KRS 527.020: http://lrc.ky.gov/KRS/527-00/070.PDF

Court of Justice facilities (this is circuit court, district court and circuit clerk facilities; also KY appeals and SC facilities).  This is NOT a county courthouse with public offices.

Detention Facilities under authority of KRS 520.050: http://lrc.ky.gov/KRS/520-00/050.PDF

Cannot carry concealed in a BAR; can carry openly as long as the firearm is unloaded under KRS 244.125; most resteraunts are exempted from this so read the statute.

http://forum.opencarry.org/forums/forumdisplay.php?101-Kentucky

title: For Sale:  WW2 M1 garand bayonet /fighting knife with sheath -Famous 317th infantry used item - Historical bayonet -
postcontent:
For sale is a classic WW2 M1 Garand Bayonet -fighting knife.  This saw action during world war II.  The bayonet and sheath are in very nice condition.  This is a peice that will compliment anyones collection or the end of a carbine.  The asking price for this bayonet is $495 or best offer and partial trades for foid items, Stihl power equipment, ATV's with titles will be considered.  
Below is an excerpt from a book written by the descendants of Andy Adkins-WW2 veteran and 317th member.  The above bayonet was one that was used by this group and the role that they played in liberating Europe during the D-Day post invasion fighting.  This is a truly historic bayonet and is a talking peice in and of itself.  This will really compliment your carbine.  

You Can’t Get Much Closer Than This  <>  Combat with Company H, 317th Infantry Regiment, 80th Division <> New Condition <>  258 pages, illustrated, index, bibliography, notes - When the 80th Infantry Division completed its training in December 1943, it was shipped in stages to the United Kingdom and then on to Normandy, where it landed on August 3, 1944. There, Lieutenant Adkins and his fellow soldiers took part in light hedgerow fighting that served to shake the division down and familiarize the troops and their officers with combat. The first real test came on August 20, 1944, when the 2d Battalion, 317th Infantry, attacked high ground near Argentan during the Allied drive to seal huge German forces in the Falaise Pocket. While scouting for mortar positions in the woods, Andy Adkins ran into a group of Germans and shot one of them dead with his carbine. This baptism in blood taught him the answer to a question every novice combatant wants to hear: He was cool under fire, capable of killing when facing the enemy. He later wrote, "It was a sickening sight, but having been caught up in the heat of battle, I didn't have a reaction other than feeling I had saved my own life." Thereafter, the 2nd Battalion, 317th Infantry, took part in a succession of bloody battles across France. Ineptly led through the tenures of several battalion commanders, the unit suffered grievous losses even as it took hills and towns away from brave and well-led German army veterans. In the course of fighting graphically portrayed in this soldier's memoir, Andy Adkins acted with remarkable skill and courage, placing himself at the forefront of the action whenever he could. His extremely aggressive delivery of critical supplies to a cutoff unit in an embattled French town earned him a Bronze Star Medal
